insights and tricks in web development: HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and ilk

CSS attribute on img
filter: invert();
negates colours for a good cheap dark-mode, without editing the image itself, as in e.g. Anki templates

CSS to automatically comma-separate items in a container, like Python's ", ".join(l):
#parent > span ~ span::before {
    content: ", ";
}

a div extends from left edge to right edge, full width, unless its width is explicitly set in CSS, hence a bias in relative positioning on large screens

for reasons i struggle to grasp, the following line in <head> is very important to help a page look right on mobile:
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">

Array.some() and Array.every() work vaguely like Python any() and all(), respectively
